Model validation is a big issue

points covered here:

  • what is validation?

  • the purpose of SDMs

  • criteria for SDM adequacy

  • current 'SDM-validation' practices

  • suggestions for improvement

Model validation is a very important topic throughout science, touching on the scientific method itself. Here we'll concentrate on some aspects that are especially relevant for SDMs, but it is still a small selection of topics that are relevant.

What is validation?

  • perhaps not a good term, better: evaluation (Oreskes, 1998)

  • Three imporant questions (Beck,2002):
    • were approved materials & methods used for model construction?
    • does it approximate the 'real thing' well?
    • does it serve its intended purpose?

The meaning of validation in the natural sciences has been discussed intensively. The current consensus: validation is (sensu stricto) very rarely possible, hence the term evaluation.

Beck (2002) summarizes the three key-questions well. However this publication does focus on concept-based rather than data-based models (with the former, a large part of the model structure is provided apriori with the latter it is to be derived). Data-based models are usually more sensitive to choices in data splitting and performance metrics, and the intended purposes are often limited to prediction only.

right materials & methods?

Data

- predictor variables
    - quality
    - resolution
    - realism
- occurrence/abundance data
    - quality
    - size

Method

- appropriate/balanced workflow 
   - model-type/algorithm
   - training/testing cycle
   - error-metrics
- quality checks/reproducibility
First a short note about the 'quality-assurance' question in model evaluation. It is split in a 'data' and a 'methods' part, but there are some cross-overs (e.g. certain types of data should only be used with certain models). While it seems feasible to assess the quality of an SDM-study/model by considering these aspects, it isn't done in practice. With regard to some aspects (e.g. quality of predictor variables) there is simply lack of knowledge ; for others (appropriate workflow) there is no concensus, and with regard to reproducibility we still lack a platform to do so (hence ZON ).

the purpose of SDMs

  • predict where a species occurs
  • suggest why a species does(n't) occur somewhere

Other reasons to construct a model (f.i.):

  • encode contemporary knowledge about a system unambiguously
  • provide exploratory tool to generate ideas and make ignorance explicit
  • communicate scientific notions to a non-expert audience

Now we jump to question 3: does a model serve its intended purpose?

Most SDM-studies aim just at predicting. The output from SDMs is used as input for subsequent analyses, interpretation or decision making.

Sometimes SDM-output is used to identify variables or processes that might be important for the distribution of a species. I don't think that SDMs are useful for the latter three model-aims.

when does an SDM achieve its purpose?

How to measure predictive performance?

- choice of index/indices
- splitting data for training & testing (evaluating)
- avoiding artifacts & comparing across studies

How to learn from a model?

- interpreting differences among models
- deal with scale-effects
- avoid over-interpretation of statistical relations

So when is an SDM performing well?

Regarding predictive performance, there are three main issues (most of the methodological SDM literature does focus on these): which performance metric to use, how to choose data for training and testing, and how to avoid mis-interpretation of the metrics + comparison across studies.

For the aim to learn from a model, there are totally different issues, We will not focus on these here.

When does an SDM predict well?

  • high score for performance index on unseen data
    • AUC, TSS (or any other index based on conf.matrix)
    • metrics of spatial overlap (e.g. Schoener's index)
  • consistency in response functions for different data

important issues:

  • absolute scores of indices often case-dependent
    • comparison to null model is important
    • conflicting results among studies (for unknown reasons)
  • sensitivity of outcome to arbitrary or undocumented model choices

We are still very far from an answer to the question, but research is ongoing

  • in search for 'good' performance metrics
  • to quantify dependence of metric-scores on all sorts of boundary conditions
  • to compare among studies (using some sort null-model is still the best option Raes & ter Steege,2007; Hijmans, 2012))
  • to consider measures of spatial overlap (rather than non-spatial aggregate metrics).

A note about performance indices

Who has a favourite?

  • Which one(s)?

Arguments in favour of/against using an index?

  • has been used previously in similar studies
  • can be calculated, given the constraints
  • has desirable properties (which properties?)

These three reasons (has been used in similar studies; can be calculated; has desirable properties) are often used to support the use of an error metric.

There is a danger in adopting the first two: we may be using inappropriate metrics for a long time.

But with regard to properties of metrics - many of these are still to be discovered. It will be valuable to quantify & document as much properties of the various indices as possible - a task where ZON could help.

the ideal index doesn't exist (sorry)

A single ideal metric does not exist. This is just one of the many illustrations showing how a metric may be sensitive to certain system or data properties - in this case prevalence.

Why is data splitting needed at all?

If you wouldn't, your model would 'overfit' your data. The image comes from a note by Scott Fortman-Roe. It shows that if you would just try to find the best model on a given data set and evaluate it on that data set, it would describe pattern + noise in that data perfectly (Training Error). By evaluating on an independent data set (Prediction Error for New Data), you test whether a model is in fact predicting the patterns while ignoring noise.

It is important to note that train-test cycles are required to build/calibrate a model in the first place, and on top of that a separate (unseen) data set data is required to properly evaluate the final model.

Different ways to split

single data source/survey

  • split once
  • cross-validation random/unstratified
  • cross-validation stratified
  • different part of spatio/temporal domain

There are various ways to split data (both during the training phase as well as the model evaluation phase). These four possibilities are ordered from less to more rigorous.

When splitting the data e.g. geographically the performance metrics for the evaluation data will be lower than when splitting data randomly.

Different ways to split

different data sources/surveys

  • split once
  • cross-over designs (train on one, evaluate on others)
  • etc.
When different data sets are availabe, this offers the opportunity to calibrate on one/some of the sets and then evaluate on the other(s) (and vice versa).

Model evaluation with various data sources

Randin et al. (2006) conducted this study using two independent plant occurrence data sets for the alps. The data differed by source and also covered different parts of the Alps. They used a very rigorous cross-over model evaluation design.

Synthetic data in model validation

  • correct model
  • incorrect model
  • different levels of noise (e.g. random predictors)
  • etc.

Also synthetic data can play an important role in model validation, quite complementary to field-data. With synthetic data it is possible to exclude any differences between the model-concept and the system. So in that case it is possible to evaluate the working of an SDM-workflow separately from any system-misrepresentation.

In addition, the point where an algorihm breaks down with increasing levels of system mis-representation or noise can be investigated. Many study use synthetic data (often together with field observations) to evaluate SDM methods.

Fresh ideas

  • make evaluation spatially explicit
  • explore relation between predictor resolution, model resolution and predictive performance
  • apply the concepts of 'behavioural models' & equifinality

There is still a lot to do on SDM model-evaluation. Here are some ideas:

  • develop tools to analyse model performance in a spatially explicty way (where does a model perform well/poor)
  • discover relations between resolution of predictor variables, the resolution of an SDM and predictive performance
  • derive & analyse 'behavoural models' rather than a single best model (in general, if multiple criteria are used, a set of 'acceptable models' will result anyway)
  • various model-types and variable combinations may result in the same outcome (equifinality) exploring the properties of these models may lead to new insights

Think spatially

And the role of ZON?

  • (e.g.) implement the functions for cross-validation in ENMeval Muscarella et al (2014)
  • design, test & share your own ideal model evaluation workflow

In many of the issues that were discussed in this presentation ZON could play a role.

Right now there are some demo-scripts to show how different types of cross-validation could be implemented. A next step could be to implement more sophisticated functions, e.g. adopting the cross-validation tools in ENMeval.

Also designing your own ideal workflow (for a given case study or more broadly) would help a lot to build a viable platform.
